Structure of the dataset

str(dataset)

The Variables

Info about Other Projects (useless)

  • PROJECT 1 (immunogram): Participation in immunogram project (likely a binary flag).
  • PROJECT 2 (dNLR prebaseline DELTA): Participation in project regarding delta neutrophil-to-lymphocyte ratio before baseline.
  • PROJECT 3 (dNLR score profiles): Participation in project related to dNLR score profiles.
  • PROJECT 4 (AI + IO): Participation in artificial intelligence and immuno-oncology project.

Personal Info about the Patients

  • Hospital: Code or name of the treating hospital.
  • ID (Clinic Number): Patients clinical identification number.
  • Date of birth: Patients date of birth.
  • Sex: Biological sex of the patient.
  • Smoking: Patients smoking history (e.g., current, former).
  • Smoker: Whether the patient has ever smoked (yes/no).
  • PY: Pack-years smoked.
  • KG: Weight in kilograms.
  • HEIGHT: Height in centimeters.
  • BMI: Body Mass Index.

Diagnosis

  • Date of diagnosis: Initial diagnosis date of lung cancer.
  • T: Tumor size/staging (TNM system).
  • N: Lymph node involvement (TNM system).
  • M: Metastasis status (TNM system).
  • Stage at diagnosis (8th ed): Overall stage based on TNM, 8th edition.
  • Date of diagnosis at advanced disease (AD): Date when advanced disease was diagnosed.
  • Stage at diagnosis AD (8th ed): Stage of advanced disease.
  • PS at diagnosis AD: Performance status at the time of advanced disease diagnosis.

Metastasis Locations

  • Mets sites at diagnosis AD: Sites of metastasis at AD diagnosis.
  • N# Mets sites: Number of metastatic sites.
  • Lung (only M1): Presence of metastasis in lung (M1 only).
  • Pleural: Presence of pleural metastasis.
  • Pericard: Presence of pericardial metastasis.
  • Lymph nodes (only M1): M1 metastasis in lymph nodes.
  • Bone: Presence of bone metastasis.
  • Adrenal: Presence of adrenal metastasis.
  • Liver: Presence of liver metastases.
  • Soft tissue: Metastases in soft tissues.
  • Brain: Brain metastases.
  • Leptomeningeal: Involvement of leptomeninges.
  • Skin: Cutaneous metastases.
  • Peritoneal: Peritoneal involvement.
  • Renal: Kidney metastases.
  • Pancreas: Pancreatic metastases.
  • Others (specify): Any other metastasis location not listed.

Diagnosis, Biopsy, and Molecular Profile

  • Date of last visit/death: Most recent follow-up or date of death.
  • Event OS = DEATH YES: Indicator of death (for overall survival).
  • Lost to FU: Patient lost to follow-up.
  • Reason of death: Cause of death.
  • Date of initial biopsy: Date when the first biopsy was performed.
  • N# biopsy INITIAL: Number of biopsies at diagnosis.
  • Bx initial Site: Anatomical site of the initial biopsy.
  • Histology: Histologic classification (e.g., adenocarcinoma).
  • Histology Pattern: Specific histological growth pattern.
  • PD-L1 performed: Whether PD-L1 testing was done.
  • Antibody: Type of antibody used for PD-L1 test.
  • PD-L1 (TC %): Tumor cell PD-L1 expression percentage.
  • Neg. PD-L1 IHC: PD-L1 negative by immunohistochemistry.
  • 1% / 1-49% / 50% PD-L1 IHC: PD-L1 expression brackets.
  • N# BIOPSY: Total number of biopsies performed.
  • N# bx for Molecular (tissue): Number of biopsies for molecular testing.
  • Site / Timepoint: Location and time of molecular testing.
  • NGS, Technique, nCounter, RT-PCR, Other: Molecular techniques used.
  • Molecular profile (ALL together): Summary of mutations/fusions/CNVs.
  • [EGFR, KRAS, ALK, ROS1, MET, etc.]: Mutation or fusion status for major oncogenic drivers.
  • Others (amp, mut, fusion): Other alterations not specified.
  • Liquid biopsy / Date: Whether a liquid biopsy was performed and when.
  • Results / Comments: Outcomes and remarks from liquid biopsy.

Progression after Immunotherapy (iPD) & New Lesions

  • Locations iPD: Sites of progression during immunotherapy.
  • N# locations (M1) iPD: Number of metastatic sites at iPD.
  • [Organ-specific iPD variables]: Progression presence in each organ.
  • New lesions at iPD: Whether new lesions appeared.
  • Liver new, Brain new, Lung new, OTHER New: Specific new lesion sites.

Immune-related Toxicity (iTOX)

  • iTOX yes (AE>G2): Presence of significant (grade >2) toxicity.
  • Toxicity Grade / Type: Severity and kind of adverse event.
  • Date start/end: Timing of toxicity.
  • TREATMENT symptomatic / Steroid / Immunosuppressor: Treatment type.
  • Comments on toxicity and treatment evolution: Narrative data.
  • Corticosteroids before IO: Whether corticosteroids were used at baseline.
  • Dose; prednisone-equivalent / Reason: Dose and reason for steroid use.

Lab Tests (PRE, Baseline, C2, CT, etc.)

  • [Hb, Leucocytes, Neutrophils, Lymphocytes, Platelets, LDH, CRP, Albumin]: Blood parameters.
  • pre, Baseline IO, C2, 1stCT: Lab values at different timepoints before treatment, at first/second cycles, or before first radiological exam.
  • >ULN: Indicates values above upper limit of normal.

Therapy Lines and Response (for each line of treatment 1L to 6L)

  • Treatment type: e.g., monotherapy or combination.
  • Start and end date
  • Best response: Complete Response, Partial, Stable Disease, or Progression.
  • PD_XL: Progression during this line of treatment.
  • Date of progression, Sites, and Type: Details on when/where/how progression occurred.
  • Criteria: Criteria used to evaluate response (e.g., RECIST).

Pre-processing

First technique

To a better use of the dataset, a normalization of the names of the columns/variables is preferible

dataset <- dataset %>%
 rename_with(~ tolower(.) %>%              #better using lowercase characters
                gsub(" ", "_", .) %>%      #better using underscores instead of whitespaces
                gsub("-", "_", .) %>%      #better removing special characters (-)
                gsub("\\(|\\)", "", .))    #better removing special characters (())

#colnames(dataset)

Second technique

How to manipulate date columns (only some of them have our interest : date_of_birth, date_of_diagnosis, date_of_last_visit/death, date_start_1l, date_pd__1l, date_end_1l)

date_cols <- names(dataset)[sapply(dataset, function(x) any(grepl("\\d{2}/\\d{2}/\\d{4}", na.omit(x))))]

Its better to have explicitly the age of the patients (from date_of_birth column)
But attention, because the dataset started to be created some years before now, so if we extrapolated the age in respect to now the ages of the patients could be wrong to the ones at the moment of diagnosis (date_of_diagnosis) (we saw before the distribution and it was was shifted to the right with respect to the generic distributions obtained in the analysis among patients affected by lung cancer); in the very rare case when we dont have the date of diagnosis, then we use the date of today as date reference from which the ages can be evaluated

1. DATE OF BIRTH

sum(is.na(dataset$date_of_birth))
## [1] 2
length(dataset$date_of_birth)
## [1] 1117

date_of_birth has only the 0,17% of missing values -> perfect candidate for the imputation

But in which format are they ?

dataset %>%
  filter(!is.na(date_of_birth)) %>%
  mutate(pattern = case_when(
    grepl("^\\d{2}-\\d{2}-\\d{4}$", date_of_birth) ~ "dd-mm-yyyy",
    grepl("^\\d{2}/\\d{2}/\\d{4}$", date_of_birth) ~ "dd/mm/yyyy",
    grepl("^\\d{4}-\\d{2}-\\d{2}$", date_of_birth) ~ "yyyy-mm-dd",
    grepl("^\\d{4}/\\d{2}/\\d{2}$", date_of_birth) ~ "yyyy/mm/dd",
    grepl("^\\d{2}\\.\\d{2}\\.\\d{4}$", date_of_birth) ~ "dd.mm.yyyy",
    TRUE ~ "altro / non riconosciuto"
  )) %>%
  count(pattern) %>%
  arrange(desc(n))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   pattern                      n
##   <chr>                    <int>
## 1 dd/mm/yyyy                 801
## 2 altro / non riconosciuto   314

The reason why we have some values like 14121, 16519, etc. is because those are not readable string dates, but Excel serial numbers, i.e.dates saved as integers.

dataset <- dataset %>%
  mutate(
    # Step 1: cleaning the spaces characters
    date_of_birth = str_trim(date_of_birth),
    date_of_birth = str_replace_all(date_of_birth, "\\s+", "")
  )

# Step 2: initial parsing with dmy()
dataset$date_of_birth_clean <- suppressWarnings(dmy(dataset$date_of_birth))

# Step 3: fallback for dates with "-" 
dataset$date_of_birth_clean[is.na(dataset$date_of_birth_clean)] <- suppressWarnings(
  dmy(gsub("-", "/", dataset$date_of_birth[is.na(dataset$date_of_birth_clean)]))
)

# Step 4: final fallback  for the numeric values (Excel)
dataset$date_of_birth_clean[is.na(dataset$date_of_birth_clean)] <- suppressWarnings(
  as.Date(as.numeric(dataset$date_of_birth[is.na(dataset$date_of_birth_clean)]), origin = "1899-12-30") # It's the one used by Excel to count the days
)

dataset$date_of_birth <- dataset$date_of_birth_clean
dataset <- select(dataset, -date_of_birth_clean)
sum(is.na(dataset$date_of_birth))
## [1] 2
length(dataset$date_of_birth)
## [1] 1117

Evaluating the age of the patients at the moment of diagnosis when its an available info (quite always), if not in respect to today (very few values)

dataset <- dataset %>%
  mutate(
    age = case_when(
      !is.na(date_of_birth) & !is.na(date_of_diagnosis) ~ floor(interval(date_of_birth, date_of_diagnosis) / years(1)),
      !is.na(date_of_birth) & is.na(date_of_diagnosis)  ~ floor(interval(date_of_birth, Sys.Date()) / years(1)),
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    )
  )
sum(is.na(dataset$age))
## [1] 2
length(dataset$age)
## [1] 1117

0,17% of missing values -> perfect candidate for the imputation

In this case (only 2 missing values) the use of MICE fo the imputation could be excessive (possible overfitting, useless complex computation), so we follow the standard technique of replacing the NA values with the median of the variable

dataset$age[is.na(dataset$age)] <- median(dataset$age, na.rm = TRUE)
sum(is.na(dataset$age))
## [1] 0

Also date_pd__1l and date_start_1l are important since their difference leads us to consider the possible response variable PROGRESSION. We use the same procedure on the date_of_last_visit_death variable, because it helps us to better manipulate the PROGRESSION, in the case where in the dataset the date_pd__1l is empty.

Particular (logical) imputation technique

Cleaning of two other variables (pd_1l_yes=1, event_os=_death_yes ) linked to the imputation techinque for the date_pd__1l

dataset <- dataset %>%
  mutate(`pd_1l_yes=1` = case_when(
    `pd_1l_yes=1` %in% c("UNK", "NA") ~ NA_real_,
    TRUE ~ as.numeric(`pd_1l_yes=1`)
  ))
dataset <- dataset %>%
  mutate(`event_os=_death_yes` = case_when(
    `event_os=_death_yes` %in% c("UNK") ~ NA_real_,
    TRUE ~ as.numeric(`event_os=_death_yes`)
  ))
# Conditional substituting for the date_pd_1l (it's already a technique for the imputation)
dataset <- dataset %>%
  mutate(
    date_pd__1l = if_else(
      is.na(date_pd__1l) & (is.na(`pd_1l_yes=1`) | `pd_1l_yes=1` == 0) & `event_os=_death_yes` == 1,
      `date_of_last_visit/death`,
      date_pd__1l
    )
  )
sum(is.na(dataset$date_pd__1l))
## [1] 441
length(dataset$date_pd__1l)
## [1] 1117

But in some case there is the default date 1899-12-30, so we replace it with a NA value

dataset <- dataset %>%
  mutate(
    date_pd__1l = if_else(
      date_pd__1l == as.Date("1899-12-30"),
      as.Date(NA),
      date_pd__1l
    )
  )
sum(is.na(dataset$date_pd__1l))
## [1] 444
length(dataset$date_pd__1l)
## [1] 1117

We have recovered 21 values (before the missing values were 465)

Definition of other two possible important/meaningful variables

1.time_to_l1_start

dataset <- dataset %>%
  mutate(
    time_to_l1_start = if_else(
      !is.na(date_start_1l) & !is.na(date_of_diagnosis),
      as.numeric(date_start_1l - date_of_diagnosis),

#Response: method K-means

data_filtered <- dataset %>% filter(progression >= 0)

# K-means (for 3 categories)
set.seed(123)
x_mat <- matrix(data_filtered$progression, ncol = 1)
k <- 3
kmeans_result <- kmeans(x_mat, centers = k)

centroids <- kmeans_result$centers[, 1]
cluster_order <- order(centroids)
data_filtered$progression_cat <- match(kmeans_result$cluster, cluster_order)

# 
data_filtered$progression_cat <- factor(data_filtered$progression_cat,
                                     levels = 1:k,
                                     labels = c("bad_responder", "medium_no_responder", "good_responder"))
ggplot(data_filtered, aes(x = progression_cat)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "steelblue") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Responder Groups (from TTP) after the First Line",
       x = "",
       y = "") +
  theme_minimal()

table(data_filtered$progression_cat)
## 
##       bad_responder medium_no_responder      good_responder 
##                 458                 188                  21
data_filtered %>%
  group_by(progression_cat) %>%
  summarise(
    min = min(progression),
    min_months = round(min(progression) / 30.44, 2),
    max = max(progression),
    max_months = round(max(progression) / 30.44, 2)
  ) %>%
  print()
